infection: A 35-year-old Snohomish County man lands at Sea-Tac Airport from a trip to Wuhan, China.
Public-health officials announce that the Snohomish County man has COVID-19, the first confirmed case in the U.S.
messaging: John Wiesman, Washington state's secretary of health, says: "We believe the risk to the public is low."

Situation report from the Department of Health: "Washington State has made improvements in our capacity to respond to disease outbreaks. We are now better poised to respond to this new threat quickly and collaboratively."
Experts express little concern about the novel coronavirus spreading in the U.S. and say Washington is well prepared.

action: City of Sammamish cancels Lunar New Year celebration over coronavirus fears.

infection: Life Care Center of Kirkland calls 911 for a resident with trouble breathing. A firefighter who responded was exposed to COVID-19 but later tested negative, according to a union representative.
action: Gov. Jay Inslee asks federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention to screen passengers arriving at Sea-Tac for temperature and recent health history.
action2: Situation report: DOH is developing take-home kits for people under public-health monitoring but is constrained by supply-chain shortages.

infection: First known case of person-to-person transmission in the U.S. is recorded in Chicago.
messaging: “We think we have it very well under control,” President Trump said. “We have very little problem in this country at this moment — five — and those people are all recuperating successfully."

action: U.S. bars travelers from entering who have been to China in previous 14 days, excluding U.S. citizens and their family.
Situation report: DOH asks federal officials about the shelf life of expired N95 masks in a state warehouse.

messaging: DOH website: "While the current situation poses a public health threat, we have no evidence the virus is spreading in Washington so the risk to the general public is low."

infection: Life Care Center recognizes an uptick in residents with respiratory illness.
messaging: President Trump: "A lot of people think that goes away in April with the heat, as the heat comes in. Typically, that will go away in April. We’re in great shape, though."

action: Situation report: DOH delivered a package of 13 "non-pharmaceutical interventions" to agency executives.

infection: Life Care resident taken to EvergreenHealth Medical Center later tests postive for coronavirus.
action: A state investigator visits Life Care regarding a suspected case of tuberculosis, finds all infection-control measures in order and no residents in isolation.

infection: A Life Care resident in his 50s is hospitalized and later dies at Harborview Medical Center after testing positive for COVID-19.
messaging: "The Coronavirus is very much under control in the USA," President Trump tweets. "Stock Market starting to look very good to me!"

infection: A man in his 50s and a woman in her 80s, both of whom had been at Life Care, die and are later revealed to have tested positive for COVID-19.
infection2: EvergreenHealth calls PHSKC about two patients with unexplained pneumonia; one of them was a Life Care resident.
action: Northshore School District Superintendent Michelle Reid closes Bothell High School for deep cleaning in response to an employee's possible exposure to COVID-19.
messaging: Public Heath Seattle - King County (PHSKC): "Currently, the health risk for COVID-19 in the United States is considered low to the general public and to Washingtonians."

infection: EvergreenHealth calls PHSKC about two patients with unexplained pneumonia; one of them was a Life Care resident.
messaging: President Donald Trump: “It’s going to disappear. One day — it’s like a miracle — it will disappear."

infection: PHSKC staff get a call from another nearby hospital reporting a patient, a Life Care employee, with signs of COVID-19.
infection2: State and local public-health officials announce two new cases of COVID-19.
messaging: DOH announces two additional positive COVID-19 tests, saying it has the potential to become a serious threat. Officials say there's no strong evidence of person-to-person transmission.

infection: PHSKC announces the nation's first death due to coronavirus, and three more COVID-19 cases. More than 50 people associated with Life Care are ill and being tested.
action: Gov. Inslee declares emergency after first confirmed death from COVID-19 and outbreak at Life Care.

messaging: DOH website: "The risk of exposure is increasing for people who live in communities in Washington state with reported spread of COVID-19, though risk is still relatively low."

infection: North Carolina identifies its first case of COVID-19, a person who had been exposed at Life Care in Kirkland.

messaging: DOH website: "The risk of exposure is increasing for people who live in Washington state."

action: Situation report: There are signs of an "unsustainable hoarding cycle." DOH received supplies from the Strategic National Stockpile but didn't get everything it requested.
messaging: Vice President Pence meets with Inslee and promises support

infection: More than 33,000 fans attend Sounders game at CenturyLink Field, where a part-time stadium worker tested positive in late February, with public health officials recommending people at higher risk of infection stay home.

action: Situation report: "The virus that causes COVID-19 seems to be spreading easily and sustainably in the community"
messaging: President Trump: "We’re prepared, and we’re doing a great job with it. And it will go away. Just stay calm. It will go away.”

action: Inslee bans gatherings of more than 250 people.
messaging: World Health Organization designates COVID-19 as a pandemic.

action: Proclamation: All K-12 schools, public and private, must close until April 24 in King, Pierce and Snohomish counties.
Inslee bans dining in restaurants, limits all public gatherings.
